When using the maxResults parameter with a value of 0, this will return a "total" value, which is useful for retrieving a Count.

However, the value of 0 is being replaced with 1, and returned as JSON includes "maxResults":1.
{code:java}
{"expand":"schemes","schemes":[{"self":"https://JIRAURLREPLACED","id":11900,"name":"Default priority scheme","description":"This is default priority scheme used by all projects without any other scheme assigned","defaultOptionId":"3","optionIds":["10001","10004","10002","2","3","4","10003","10100"],"defaultScheme":true}],"startAt":0,"maxResults":1,"total":2}{code}
In this case, it would be preferable to just retrieve the Count and not alter the command as sent.

Our documentation at [https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftwareserver/advanced-searching-operators-reference-939938745.html] states:
{quote}Find all issues where the Summary contains the exact phrase "full screen" (see Search syntax for text fields for details on how to escape quote-marks and other special characters):
{code:java}
summary ~ "\"full screen\""
{code}
{quote}
That creates the expectation that we can do an exact search on Text fields, while Lucene will return similar matches due to the stemming process.
 Thus, when users do a search like
{code:java}
"Projeto Gitlab"  ~ "\" wkl_ek4_api_cartoes \""
{code}
It will also returns:
 wkl_ek4_api_cartoes
 test_wkl_ek4_api_cartoes
 wkl_ek4_api_cartoes_test
